Russia debates its future
JAROSLAVL: Many say that Russia lacks a "civil society."
But it partially compensates with what is quite an interesting public sphere where serious topics are debated, and fleeting glimpses of the powerful are not limited to TV clips alone.
In the first two weeks of September, there were consecutive conferences of two important Russian political groups, the Valdai Discussion Club and the Global Policy Forum.
The former took place on a ship and ended with a dinner with Prime Minister Vladimir Putin in Sochi on the Black Sea.
Letzteres in Jaroslawl kulminierte in einem Symposium mit Präsident Dmitri Medwedew.
Wissenschaftler, Mitglieder von Denkfabriken und Journalisten (sowie russische und ausländische) diskutierten gemeinsam mit wichtigen Politikern und Unternehmensführern über Russlands Zukunft.
Drei Dinge machten diese Veranstaltungen auf typisch russische Weise zu etwas Besonderem.
Das Erste war das intensive Medieninteresse.
Sogar ein äußerst kamerascheuer Wissenschaftler konnte sich plötzlich als russischer Fernsehstar wiederfinden.
The second was the willingness of both Putin and Medvedev to publicly engage with experts on their own intellectual turf.
The only Western political leader of recent times who had the confidence to do this comes to mind; that was Bill Clinton.
Finally, the two events marked the emergence of competing political forums, each exuding the faint but unmistakable scent of an impending conflict.
To those with eyes to see, these two conferences offered a fascinating glimpse into a crumbling diarchy.
The main theme of the Valdai Conference was whether Russia's history and geography condemned it to authoritarian rule.
Falls der Demokratie die Zukunft gehört, sei es dann Russlands Schicksal, das zu verpassen?
The pessimists – especially Russian historians – argued that it would be difficult if not impossible for Russia to overcome its autocratic legacy.
Lew Belousov from the State Lomonosov University in Moscow argued that autocracy in Russia – supported by the passivity and endurance of the Russians – would rise again like a phoenix from the ashes.
The Bolsheviks had inherited autocracy from the tsars; Putin had rediscovered the old monarchical principle of anointing his successor and thus bypassed democratic competition for the presidency.
Radicals like Vladimir Ryshkov rejected this historical determinism. One should, according to Ryshkov, not legitimize authoritarianism by referring to history.
The protests were increasing.
It was Putin's yoke, not that of history, that weighed heavily on Russia.
A lot was missing from this discussion in terms of clarity, as such discussions often tend to be.
The majority of participants failed to distinguish between history as a limitation and history as a determinant.
Countries and civilizations can never fully overcome their history, but every history offers many different possibilities.
Länder sind nicht genetisch programmiert wie Tiere.
Die Diskussion über die Autokratie war unweigerlich mit der anderer Themen verknüpft.
Man hat die Autokratie in Russland als für ein Weltreich notwendig verteidigt.
Doch dies führt zu einer weiteren Frage: Braucht Russland ein Weltreich?
Kann Russland seiner imperialen Vergangenheit abschwören und normale Beziehungen mit seinen seit kurzem unabhängigen Nachbarn wie der Ukraine und Georgien pflegen?
Can it actually be a completely "ordinary" actor on the world stage?
At the conference in Yaroslavl with Medvedev, attention shifted to the connection between democracy and modernization.
Everyone agreed that Russia must diversify its economy and overcome its dependence on energy.
As Medvedev emphasized, an economy based on raw materials is always vulnerable to fluctuations in raw material prices.
But there are, roughly speaking, two views on the relationship between political and economic modernization.
Putin's view is that democracy arises from a modern welfare state as a kind of reward for hard work.
If the state drives modernization from above, then democracy will grow naturally, albeit slowly, as a result of increasing prosperity and a growing middle class.
The head ideologist of the Kremlin, Vladislav Surkov, has suggested that a true democracy requires a "democracy in the mind," implying that this desirable mental state is still far away in Russia.
The alternative view, advocated by people like Igor Yurgens, the head of Medvedev's preferred think tank, the Institute of Contemporary Development, is that democracy is a prerequisite for economic modernization.
They argue that the Russian state in its current form lacks any real incentive to reform its own poor economic practices—or those of the Russians.
The current development confirms this.
Russia has shown only a modest recovery from the recession.
There is almost no innovation; the elites are content with leading a comfortable life off the earnings from the energy business, and corruption continues unchecked.
Putin is the strong leader of a weak state, which, lacking a unifying element or feedback process, is unable to carry out a modernization project.
There is a clear divide between Putin and Medvedev.
Medvedev is anything but Putin's puppet.
Both believe that democracy must come sooner or later, but while Putin emphasizes "later," Medvedev has enriched the public discourse in Russia with a liberating voice.
Cynics claim that this is merely a misleading routine along the lines of "Good Cop, Bad Cop."
But words count, and a new rhetoric is a political force in its own right.
Medvedev's primary strategic goal now must be to secure a second term as president.
He cannot openly challenge Putin's legacy but must position himself as someone who goes beyond Putin.
This is a tricky balancing act because Putin can reclaim the presidency at any time if he believes that his former protégé wants to dismantle the authoritarian state that Putin has created.
Nineteen years after the fall of communism, Russia's direction remains as unclear as ever.
This is particularly important for the Russians, yet because Russia spans the enormous Eurasian landmass, the lack of clarity regarding Russia's future forces us to constantly be concerned.
Is Russia part of the West?
Does it give him a uniquely Eurasian perspective that can mediate a potential clash between Western and Eastern civilizations or between Christianity and Islam?
Russia cannot be neatly categorized into geopolitical categories, but it remains too important to ignore.
